        <h2>The Moons of Mars</h2>
        <div class="col-lg-6">
            <br />
            Phobos and Deimos were both discovered in 1877 by astronomer Asaph Hall.
            As for their names, Phobos, meaning fear, and Deimos, meaning panic, were named after the two horses that pulled the chariot of the counterpart to Mars, Ares.
            Since the surface materials of these moons consist of carbon and ice, researchers have assumed that the two moons are actually asteroids captured in Mars’ orbit.
            [<a href="https://solarsystem.nasa.gov/moons/mars-moons/in-depth/">REF</a>]
        </div>
